<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does it cost to sell a house in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For most sellers in Brisbane's inner east, total selling costs typically fall between 2.5% and 4% of the sale price. This includes agent commission (usually 2% to 2.75% plus GST), marketing ($3,000 to $8,000 for a well-run campaign), conveyancing ($1,200 to $2,500), and settlement adjustments for rates and water. Optional costs such as professional styling, pre-sale repairs, and building certificates add to this depending on the property and your goals."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the typical agent commission for selling a house in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Agent commission in Brisbane's inner east typically ranges from 2% to 2.75% of the sale price, plus GST. Commission is not regulated in Queensland, so it is negotiable. Agents who discount heavily on commission often offset this elsewhere, including in the quality of marketing spend or the time dedicated to your campaign. Understand what you are getting before negotiating solely on rate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do sellers pay capital gains tax when selling a house in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Capital gains tax (CGT) applies in Australia when you sell a property that is not your primary residence. If you are selling your main home, the main residence exemption generally applies and you will not pay CGT. If you are selling an investment property, CGT applies on the gain above your cost base. If you have owned the property for more than 12 months, you may be eligible for a 50% CGT discount. Consult your accountant before listing if you are unsure of your CGT position."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Costs of Selling a House in Brisbane: What Sellers Need to Budget For
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The costs of selling are real and worth understanding before you commit. Here is a clear breakdown of what you will pay, what is negotiable, and how to estimate your net return.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling costs are one of the least-discussed parts of a property transaction, yet they have a direct effect on what you actually walk away with. Most sellers focus on the sale price, which is understandable, but the gap between the price you achieve and the amount you receive after costs can be significant. Understanding those costs before you list allows you to set realistic expectations, negotiate where it matters, and avoid surprises at settlement.</p>

      <p>For a typical property in Brisbane's inner east, total selling costs generally fall somewhere between 2.5% and 4% of the sale price. On a $1.2 million home, that is $30,000 to $48,000. The exact figure depends on the agent you choose, the marketing campaign you run, your legal fees, and whether you invest in optional pre-sale work. Here is how those costs break down.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agent commission</h2>
      <p>Agent commission is the largest single cost in almost every sale. In Brisbane's inner east, commission typically ranges from 2% to 2.75% of the sale price, plus GST. On a $1.2 million sale, that is between $26,400 and $36,300 inclusive of GST at 2.5% commission. Commission is not regulated in Queensland and is fully negotiable.</p>

      <p>A common mistake is to negotiate commission down without understanding what changes as a result. Agents who work on volume at lower commission rates often dedicate less time to individual campaigns, reduce the number of buyer follow-ups, and have less flexibility to absorb marketing costs on your behalf. The relationship between commission and outcome is not linear, but the quality of your agent and their motivation to maximise your price matters significantly more than saving half a percent on their fee. The right question is not who charges the least, but who will deliver the best net result after all costs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing costs</h2>
      <p>Marketing is a separate cost from commission and is paid by the seller, typically upfront or on settlement depending on the agent's terms. A well-executed marketing campaign for an inner-east Brisbane property generally costs between $3,000 and $8,000. This covers professional photography (including floor plans and sometimes drone footage), listing fees on realestate.com.au and Domain, a signboard, and print advertising if relevant to your buyer demographic.</p>

      <p>Some agents offer a package that bundles marketing into their commission rate. These arrangements can work, but understand what is actually included before agreeing. A $300 photography package is not the same as a $1,200 one, and the difference shows in how buyers perceive your property before they visit. Under-investing in marketing consistently produces weaker enquiry and lower attendance at open homes, which translates directly to fewer competitive offers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Conveyancing and solicitor fees</h2>
      <p>You will need a solicitor or conveyancer to handle the legal side of the transaction: reviewing the contract, responding to requisitions from the buyer's solicitor, and handling the transfer of title at settlement. Solicitor fees for a standard residential sale in Queensland typically range from $1,200 to $2,500, depending on the complexity of the transaction and the firm you use. If there are easements, encumbrances, or other complications on your title, fees may be higher.</p>

      <p>It is worth using a solicitor with experience in Queensland residential property rather than a generalist firm. The contract process in Queensland has specific requirements and a solicitor who handles these transactions regularly will navigate them more efficiently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement adjustments: rates and water</h2>
      <p>At settlement, your solicitor will calculate an adjustment for council rates, water rates, and body corporate levies if applicable. If you have paid rates in advance for the quarter, the buyer reimburses you for the period from settlement to the end of the paid period. If rates are in arrears, you pay the shortfall. These adjustments are typically small, often a few hundred dollars either way, but they appear on your settlement statement and affect your net proceeds.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mortgage discharge fees</h2>
      <p>If you have a mortgage on the property, your lender will charge a discharge fee to release their interest in the title at settlement. Discharge fees vary by lender, but typically range from $150 to $600. Some lenders also charge a break cost if you are breaking a fixed-rate loan before the fixed term ends. If you are in a fixed-rate period, contact your lender before listing to understand any break costs, as these can be significant depending on interest rate movements since you fixed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains tax</h2>
      <p>If you are selling your primary residence, the main residence exemption generally means you will not pay capital gains tax (CGT). If the property has been your primary home for the entire period of ownership, you are typically fully exempt.</p>

      <p>If you are selling an investment property, CGT applies on the gain above your cost base (purchase price plus acquisition costs plus capital improvements). If you have owned the property for more than 12 months, you may be eligible for the 50% CGT discount, which effectively halves the taxable gain before it is added to your income. CGT is not a transaction cost in the same sense as commission or legal fees, but for investment sellers it can be the largest single financial consequence of the sale. Speak to your accountant well before listing to understand your position and whether there are any strategies worth considering around the timing of settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Optional costs: styling, repairs, and building certificates</h2>
      <p>Beyond the non-negotiable costs above, many sellers choose to invest in pre-sale preparation. Professional property styling typically costs between $2,500 and $6,000 for a furnished property in Brisbane's inner east, depending on the size of the home and how many rooms are included. The data on styling is reasonably consistent: well-styled properties attract stronger enquiry and more emotionally engaged buyers, which tends to support price. For family homes and character properties in the inner east, styling frequently returns more than it costs in the final outcome.</p>

      <p>Pre-sale repairs and touch-ups are worth doing selectively. The items buyers use to justify reducing offers are almost always obvious: dated paint, worn carpets, broken fixtures, deferred maintenance. Addressing these before the first open home removes the buyer's objection before it is made. Your agent should tell you specifically what to address and what to leave. Not every repair adds value and overcapitalising on pre-sale work is a real risk if you are not selective.</p>

      <p>A building and pest certificate is optional but increasingly common as a pre-sale document in Brisbane. Providing one upfront gives buyers confidence and reduces the number of conditional offers you receive. It also removes the risk of a buyer discovering something unexpected during their own inspection and using it to renegotiate or withdraw. The cost is typically $450 to $700.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Estimating your net return</h2>
      <p>To calculate your net proceeds from a sale, start with your expected sale price and deduct the following: agent commission plus GST, marketing costs, solicitor fees, mortgage discharge fee if applicable, and any pre-sale investment you make. Add or subtract the settlement adjustment for rates. For investment properties, factor in the after-tax consequence of CGT separately.</p>

      <p>A worked example for a $1.2 million sale: commission at 2.5% plus GST ($33,000), marketing ($5,500), solicitor ($1,800), discharge fee ($300), styling ($4,000), and building certificate ($550) gives total costs of approximately $45,150, or about 3.75% of the sale price. Net proceeds would be approximately $1,154,850 before any CGT consideration.</p>

      <p>Understanding this figure before you commit to listing allows you to make informed decisions about your next purchase, your debt position, and whether the timing is right for your circumstances.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
